<h3 id="overview">Overview</h3>
<p>
    Exposes <code>window.customTranslations</code> for registering named <strong>translation
    providers</strong>. A provider is any source that can resolve a message key for a locale — a bundled
    MessageFormat 2.0 catalog, a lazily-loaded namespace, or a library adapter (FormatJS, i18next,
    Lingui, Paraglide). Providers are tried in registration order; the first whose
    <code>resolve()</code> returns a non-null <code>MessageFn</code> owns the message. Any consumer
    resolves the registry through the injector chain and reads messages via the <code>@t</code> context,
    so translation lookup is never hardwired into components.
</p>

<h3 id="standards">Web Standards Alignment</h3>
<table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Navigator/languages"><code>navigator.languages</code></a></td>
        <td>Baseline</td>
        <td>The default signal for negotiating the locale fallback chain the registry walks when no explicit preference is set.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://github.com/tc39/proposal-intl-messageformat"><code>Intl.MessageFormat</code></a></td>
        <td>TC39 Stage 1</td>
        <td>The forward-compatible target for providers; the registry contract is unchanged when the polyfilled MF2 provider becomes a native call.</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h3 id="interface">Interface</h3>
{% highlight "typescript" %}
interface CustomTranslationProviderRegistry extends CustomRegistry<CustomTranslationProvider> {
    readonly localName = 'customTranslations';

    // Register a named provider (e.g. 'app', 'vendor', 'lazy-checkout').
    // Registration order is priority order — first registered is tried first.
    define(name: string, provider: CustomTranslationProvider): void;

    // Ordered iterator — consumers try providers in definition order.
    values(): IterableIterator<CustomTranslationProvider>;
}
{% endhighlight %}

<h3 id="usage-example">Usage Example</h3>

{{ pluggedContent("translations-registry-example", code=true) }}
{% highlight "javascript" %}
// Register providers at bootstrap in priority order.
import { Mf2Provider } from '@web-intl/messageformat';
import { I18nextProvider } from '@web-intl/i18next';

customTranslations.define('app', new Mf2Provider({ load: (l) => import(`./locales/${l}.json`) }));
customTranslations.define('vendor', new I18nextProvider(i18nextInstance)); // adapter, equal participant

// Any consumer delegates — never knows which provider resolved the key.
for (const tag of negotiate(locale)) {          // ['fr-CA', 'fr', 'en']
    for (const provider of customTranslations.values()) {
        const message = provider.resolve(key, tag);
        if (message) return message(params);
    }
}
{% endhighlight %}

{{ unpluggedContent("translations-registry-example", code=true) }}
{% highlight "javascript" %}
consume { customTranslations } of '@web-intl';

customTranslations.define('app', new Mf2Provider({ load: (l) => import(`./locales/${l}.json`) }));

for (const provider of customTranslations.values()) {
    const message = provider.resolve(key, locale);
    if (message) return message(params);
}
{% endhighlight %}

{{ endContent() }}

<h3 id="design-decisions">Design Decisions</h3>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
    <li><strong>Registry, not a chain object.</strong> <code>CustomRegistry.values()</code> already provides ordered iteration. Registration order is the priority — explicit and reviewable. Mirrors <code>CustomRecoveryHandlerRegistry</code> and <code>CustomPositioningRegistry</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>First-that-resolves pattern.</strong> Providers return <code>null</code> to decline without side effects; resolution continues down the fallback chain and on to the next provider. Consistent with <code>CustomRecoveryHandler</code> (<code>tryRecover</code>) and route matching (<code>matchRoute</code>).</li>
    <li><strong>No built-in catalog.</strong> The registry ships no messages. Applications register the providers (bundled MF2, lazy namespaces, library adapters) they actually need — keeping the standard lean and library-agnostic.</li>
    <li><strong>Library-agnostic.</strong> Native <code>Intl</code> MF2 and every third-party engine register behind the same contract, so message catalogs from different vendors interoperate in one app.</li>
</ul>

<p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-4">
    Providers satisfy the
    <a href="/plugs/customtranslationprovider/"><code>CustomTranslationProvider</code></a> contract.
    See <a href="/projects/webintl/">Web Intl</a> for the full feature surface and
    <a href="/projects/webintl/#protocol-localization">Localization Protocol</a> for the conformance reference.
</p>
